Yoshimasa began his career in {{ill|Tenroku|ja|天禄|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 1 (970), when {{ill|Kamo no Yasunori|ja|賀茂保憲|qq=draft|qq=draft}} recommended him as a ''Tenmon Tokugōsei'' (student specializing in astronomy).<ref>''{{ill|Ruiju Fusenshō|ja|類聚符宣抄|qq=draft|qq=draft}}''</ref> In {{ill|Kanwa|ja|寛和|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 2 (986), he succeeded his father as Tenmon Hakase. By {{ill|Kankō|ja|寛弘|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 1 (1004), he was appointed Onmyō no Kami, the head of the Onmyōryō. 

Historically, the position of Onmyō no Kami had been reserved for prestigious families such as the {{ill|Kamo clan|ja|賀茂氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Ōnakatomi clan|ja|大中臣氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. However, following Yoshimasa’s appointment, the role began alternating between the Abe and Kamo clans, eventually becoming the hereditary domain of the Abe clan (later known as the {{ill|Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家|qq=draft|qq=draft}} during the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}).

Although Yoshimasa lacks the legendary anecdotes associated with his father and elder brother, his appointment as Onmyō no Kami demonstrates his significant skill and accomplishments. Notably, entries in ''{{ill|Shōyūki|ja|小右記|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'' by {{ill|Fujiwara no Sanesuke|ja|藤原実資|qq=draft|qq=draft}} indicate that Yoshimasa continued serving as Tenmon Hakase until his death on {{ill|Kan'nin|ja|寛仁|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 3, April 28 (June 4, 1019).<ref>''Shōyūki''</ref> After his passing, a replacement candidate from Iyo Province, named "Kyuho" (秦久邦), was considered but deemed unqualified due to insufficient knowledge, highlighting a talent shortage and the growing influence of local Onmyōji outside the capital.

== Debate on Heirship ==
While tradition generally identifies {{ill|Abe no Yoshihira|ja|安倍吉平|qq=draft|qq=draft}} as Abe no Seimei's eldest son and heir, some scholars propose Yoshimasa as the true heir. This view stems from the nearly identical birth years of Yoshihira and Yoshimasa, as well as Yoshimasa’s appointment as Onmyō no Kami—a role typically reserved for the eldest son in a hereditary system.<ref>Examples of this debate are reflected in modern interpretations, such as the manga ''{{ill|Onmyōji (manga)|ja|陰陽師|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'' by {{ill|Reiko Okano|ja|岡野玲子|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, where Yoshimasa is depicted as Seimei's eldest son.</ref>

However, historical records such as ''Shōyūki'' and ''{{ill|Mido Kanpakuki|ja|御堂関白記|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'' by {{ill|Fujiwara no Michinaga|ja|藤原道長|qq=draft|qq=draft}} reference Yoshihira more frequently than Yoshimasa, suggesting that Yoshihira was widely recognized as Seimei’s successor. Additionally, Yoshimasa’s son, {{ill|Abe no Narichika|ja|安倍成親|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, is sometimes identified as Yoshihira’s biological child adopted by Yoshimasa.<ref>''Abe-shi Keizu'' (''{{ill|Zoku Gunsho Ruijū|ja|続群書類従|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'').</ref>

== Family ==
* Father: {{ill|Abe no Seimei|ja|安倍晴明|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
* Mother: Unknown
* Wife: Unknown
* Children:
** Son: {{ill|Abe no Narichika|ja|安倍成親|qq=draft|qq=draft}}

Some genealogies suggest that Narichika was Yoshihira's biological son adopted by Yoshimasa. Another child, "Hōshin," appears in certain sources but is also believed to have been adopted.<ref>''Abe-shi Keizu,'' in ''{{ill|Zoku Gunsho Ruijū|ja|続群書類従|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.''</ref>

